  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (or \"clean\") by disguising their true origin. This typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting a series of complex transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Reintroducing the laundered money into the economy as apparently legitimate funds.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime because it facilitates other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and organized crime, by allowing criminals to profit from their illegal activities and integrate those profits into the legitimate economy.\n\nGovernments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious activities, and maintaining records of transactions.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences. Businesses found complicit in money laundering can also face significant reputational damage and loss of licenses.",
